
@startuml
' Class Diagram for University System

class University {
  -faculties: List<Faculty>
  -totalEmployees: int
}

class Faculty {
  -name: String
  -institutes: List<Institute>
  -dean: Dean
}

class Institute {
  -name: String
  -address: String
  -ras: List<ResearchAssistant>
}

class Employee {
  -socialSecurityNumber: String
  -name: String
  -email: String
}

class Dean {
  -employee: Employee
}

class ResearchAssistant {
  -fieldOfResearch: String
  -projects: List<Project>
  -coursesTaught: List<Course>
}

class Project {
  -name: String
  -startDate: Date
  -endDate: Date
  -hours: int
}

class Course {
  -id: String
  -name: String
  -weeklyDuration: int
}

class Lecturer {
  -researchAssistant: ResearchAssistant
}

' Relationships

University "1" --> "0..*" Faculty
Faculty "1" --> "0..*" Institute
Faculty "1" --> "1" Dean
Dean "1" --> "1" Employee

Institute "1" --> "0..*" ResearchAssistant

ResearchAssistant "1" --> "0..*" Project
ResearchAssistant "1" --> "0..*" Course
ResearchAssistant "1" --> "1" Lecturer

Project "1" --> "1" ResearchAssistant

Course "1" --> "0..*" ResearchAssistant
@enduml

### Notes:
- `Employee` is a base class, and both `Dean` and `ResearchAssistant` are derived from it (though in this model, `Dean` is modeled as a separate class with an `Employee` reference).
- A `Lecturer` is a role that a `ResearchAssistant` can take on.
- `Project` has a name, start and end date, and number of hours.
- `Course` has a unique ID, name, and weekly duration.

